<br>
     Throughout the whole movie the programs/machines hint that they must have a purpose in order to exist, without a purpose, they have no reason to exist and are deleted.  Although when some are meant to be deleted, they flee to the matrix to hide out, but this is not where i'm going.  At the architect's speech in Reloaded, he says that the purpose of the One is to compile data into his life about the anomaly that is choice.<br>
     Choice is the imperfection that makes the Matrix have its flaws.  The architect attempts to create an equation for everything (isn't math how machines think?).  Each equation, or program all together equals the Matrix itself.  The Oracle earlier says that programs were written to govern everything within the Matrix.  But how can you balance out an equation that involves something as unpredictable as a person's ability that is choice?  He goes on saying that the Matrix which resembles human history, as opposed to the very first one which was the paradise of happiness, when presented as an unconscious choice to the human population, 99% could accept it as reality, but that 1% cannot, a.k.a. those humans who live in Zion that freed themselves.  If left unchecked, that anomaly, or imbalance in the equation can cause disaster.  This is where the One comes in.  His purpose (see above) is to compile data on choice into/as his life.  Since Neo is choice, and choice is an anomaly, it imbalances the equation.  Neo isn't constrained of the Matrix equation so he can operate outside it, explaining his superman powers.  At the end of the journey of the One, he returns to the machine source, decompiling himself so the choice data can be analyzed and used to improve the Matrix, and the Matrix can be rebooted.  This has been done 6 times already, hence the 6 Neo's and 6 matrix versions.<br>
     If the One doesn't return to the source at the end of his journey, the anomaly of choice in the equation eventually causes so many errors that the Matrix will crash and everyone linked to it will die.  Example: if you leave your computer on long enough without shutting down or rebooting, it will crash.<br>
     That section above explains everything at the end of Reloaded.  Now i'll move onto how Revolutions fits in:<br>
     Towards the beginning of the movie, the Oracle explains that Smith is the opposite of Neo, just as 1 is the opposite of -1.  Neo and Smith together = 0, or neutrality.  She also explains that Neo could use his powers in the real world because he can link to the source, having the ability to overload machines in the real world, a.k.a zapping sentinels at the end of Reloaded.  He simply linked to the source, and overloaded those particular sentinels that were trying to attack him.  He was not ready for those abilities yet, which is why he fainted and was sent to the train station at the beginning of Revolutions.<br>
     *Skipping random death and mayhem scenes in Zion docks*  Now we're at the point where Neo jacks in at the machine city (01 for you Animatrix fans out there).  It's raining, weather is about as bad outside as in the real world, everything's crazy with the system which means one thing:  since Neo didn't go to the source at the end of Reloaded where he should have so the Matrix could be rebooted, the current version Matrix is starting to grow unstable because of staying on so long, the equation is spewing out too many errors because of choice.<br>
     *Skipping DBZ fight scene with Neo and Smith*  Smith has just absorbed Neo.  Remember the beginning of Revolutions? About balance?  Neo combining with Smith =1+-1=0 = balance itself.  Now the scene is split back to the machine city, it looks as if the FaceOrbThingy is sending some sort of command throughout the system, sending beams of light throughout many circuits.  Seeming like it's affecting the whole Matrix since you see the light beam run through the circuit that's jacking Neo into the Matrix.  Cut back to the fight scene.  NeoSmith is breaking apart into pure light, almost looking as if he's decompiling.<br>
     If Neo can link to the source, wouldn't it be safe to say that if Neo is currently located so close to the source, and connected too, couldn't the source link to Neo?  Remember, that Neo is supposed to be the variable that is choice, or 1.  Smith is his opposite, so he is -1.  1+-1=0.  The problem that is choice in the equation has been solved, balance has been achieved.  The source knows this, and seeing the opportunity it links to Neo and decompiles him into data, like what was supposed to happen at the end of Reloaded.  The source studies the data, using it to stabilize the system.  The Matrix has now been rebooted, the system is saved along with the machine's power supply.<br>
     Remember that Neo made a deal with the FaceOrbThingy, he deals with Smith’s invasion of the Matrix, the machines end the war and start a peace with humans.  What if the machines go back on the deal?  Look at the meeting with the Oracle and the Architect.  The Oracle asks if the Architect will keep his word.  He says (not exact) &quot;What do you think I am? Human?&quot;  Machines will keep their word.  Peace has been achieved.  Pack up the popcorn.  Movie's over.<br>
